<subSubSection id="AC3E653DA2E50DCCE1CC42A8C2C61E1B" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="4" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="1453D5846BC9973DFD2C81BFC60E9C88" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D676944A378FCCE1923E4D77B39D9B95" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<taxonomicName id="4175D9BEF0AC52E1E290FEC72ED9C9A5" class="Malacostraca" family="Ampeliscidae" genus="Ampelisca" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ampelisca brevicornis" order="Amphipoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevicornis">Ampelisca brevicornis</taxonomicName>
is known to be a cosmopolitan species and has been collected from the soft substrata and water column from the littoral zone to the continental shelf from the waters of the world except for boreal areas (
<bibRefCitation id="3EC363D15CDCCAF3943C65CEB4478B82" author="Rabindranath, P" journalOrPublisher="Hydrobiologia" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" pagination="241 - 262" title="Marine Gammaridea (Crustacea: Amphipoda) from the Indian Region; Family Ampeliscidae." url="10.1007/BF00043143" volume="46" year="1975">Rabindranath 1975</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="8AD558D4593A4E335806F1BA25048625" author="Lincoln, RJ" journalOrPublisher="British Museum, London" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" title="British Marine Amphipoda: Gammaridea." year="1979">Lincoln 1979</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="063853F186495A188AA4E90B4CA46A11" author="Hirayama, A" journalOrPublisher="Publication of Seto Marine Biological Laboratory" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="75 - 150" title="Taxonomic studies on the shallow water Gammaridean Amphipoda of the west Kyushu, Japan. 1. Acanthonotozomatidae, Ampeliscidae, Ampithoidae, Amphilochidae, Anamixidae, Argissidae, Atylidae and Colomastigidae." volume="28" year="1983">Hirayama 1983</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="B45CB86E48ED1D7C06466F23E6888D47" genus="Ampelicsa" lsidName="Ampelicsa brevicornis" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" rank="species" species="brevicornis">Ampelicsa brevicornis</taxonomicName>
was first recorded from the Mediterranean Sea (
<bibRefCitation id="3D0AA8CF456452B09949542FE7AB20C2" author="Costa, A" journalOrPublisher="Rendiconto della Societa Reale Borbonica, Academia della Scienze, new series" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="167 - 178" title="Relazione sulla memoria del DottorAchille Costa, di ricerche su' crostacei amfipodi del regno di Napoli." volume="2" year="1853">Costa 1853</bibRefCitation>
) by the name 
<taxonomicName id="059A3EC3B92413B0D724EC6111E20E98" authority="Costa, 1853" authorityName="Costa" authorityYear="1853" class="Malacostraca" family="Ampeliscidae" genus="Araneops" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Araneops brevicornis" order="Amphipoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevicornis">Araneops brevicornis</taxonomicName>
; it occurs in waters of variable temperatures from north east Atlantic (
<bibRefCitation id="36D4E0ED58B9555F38836B7B158FCD9F" author="Schellenberg, A" editor="Michaelsen, W" journalOrPublisher="L. Friedrichsohn &amp; Co., Hamburg" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" title="Crustacea. VIII: Amphipoda." year="1925">Schellenberg 1925</bibRefCitation>
), south and west Norway (
<bibRefCitation id="448AD3789690F6E3BF9C81BAC6C7B7B0" author="Sars, GO" journalOrPublisher="Amphipoda" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" pagination="1 - 711" title="An account of the Crustacea of Norway with short descriptions and figures of all the species." volume="1" year="1895">Sars 1895</bibRefCitation>
), Atlantic coast of Europe (
<bibRefCitation id="CBE4608977B8920995B537052AEEAF79" author="Lincoln, RJ" journalOrPublisher="British Museum, London" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" title="British Marine Amphipoda: Gammaridea." year="1979">Lincoln 1979</bibRefCitation>
), north Africa (
<bibRefCitation id="DD5F357A5B9B79C756DD417D63C622E6" author="Kaim-Malka, RA" journalOrPublisher="Tethys" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="927 - 975" title="Contribution a l'etude de quelques especes du genre Ampelisca (Crustacea - Amphipoda) en Mediterranee. II." volume="1" year="1969">Kaim-Malka 1969</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="0784D1F45BA193CA00DC5458BCF5B71E" author="Reid, DM" journalOrPublisher="Atlantidae Report" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" pagination="190 - 291" title="Report on the Amphipoda (Gammaridea and Caprellidea) of the Coast of Tropical West Africa." volume="2" year="1951">Reid 1951</bibRefCitation>
), Indian Ocean (
<bibRefCitation id="B74D25D427D4FA21BA52241660F72B10" author="Rabindranath, P" journalOrPublisher="Hydrobiologia" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" pagination="241 - 262" title="Marine Gammaridea (Crustacea: Amphipoda) from the Indian Region; Family Ampeliscidae." url="10.1007/BF00043143" volume="46" year="1975">Rabindranath 1975</bibRefCitation>
), Japan (
<bibRefCitation id="C345BAEC856D91F1E7131D097A8F3D99" author="Nagata, K" journalOrPublisher="Publication of Seto Marine Biological Laboratory" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" pagination="131 - 170" title="Studies on marine GammarideanAmphipoda of the Seto Inland Sea I." volume="13" year="1965 a">Nagata 1965a</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="3656078ED45B04473EAB092BC7A3A439" author="Hirayama, A" journalOrPublisher="Asian Marine Biology" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="77 - 93" title="Marine Ampeliscidae (Crustacea: Amphipoda) from Hong Kong." volume="8" year="1991">Hirayama 1991</bibRefCitation>
), Indonesian archipelago (
<bibRefCitation id="AF4AC6F640BBC5F9DA222253E28F5F64" author="Pirlot, JM" journalOrPublisher="Siboga-Expeditie" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" pagination="237 - 328" title="Les amphipodes de l'expedition du Siboga. Deuxieme partie .... II. - Les amphipodes de la mer profonde. III. Les amphipodes littoraux. I. Lysianassidae ... Gammaridae." volume="33 e" year="1936">Pirlot 1936</bibRefCitation>
) as well as the neighbouring waters of Vietnam (
<bibRefCitation id="EA0D748285471B9B6DE84DB4C6EDF95D" author="Imbach, MC" journalOrPublisher="Naga Report" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="40 - 167" title="Scientific Result of Marine Investigation of the South China Sea and Gulf of Thailand: Gammaridean Amphipoda from the South China Sea." volume="4" year="1967">Imbach 1967</bibRefCitation>
). Although several morphological variations in antennae, pleonal epimera and urosome are reported between European (
<bibRefCitation id="478E46BB63B5468625047DB456D37CAA" author="Schellenberg, A" editor="Michaelsen, W" journalOrPublisher="L. Friedrichsohn &amp; Co., Hamburg" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" title="Crustacea. VIII: Amphipoda." year="1925">Schellenberg 1925</bibRefCitation>
) and African specimens (
<bibRefCitation id="6968473B381047FED2647717E57F2F20" author="Reid, DM" journalOrPublisher="Atlantidae Report" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" pagination="190 - 291" title="Report on the Amphipoda (Gammaridea and Caprellidea) of the Coast of Tropical West Africa." volume="2" year="1951">Reid 1951</bibRefCitation>
), the present specimens agree in detail with descriptions by 
<bibRefCitation id="3631645E4BFFE75C6D7576800C795E7B" author="Imbach, MC" journalOrPublisher="Naga Report" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="40 - 167" title="Scientific Result of Marine Investigation of the South China Sea and Gulf of Thailand: Gammaridean Amphipoda from the South China Sea." volume="4" year="1967">Imbach (1967)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="DB8699CBCEFFE8550EDD73405030CB8F" author="Nagata, K" journalOrPublisher="Publication of the Seto Marine Biological Laboratory" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" pagination="67 - 82" title="Notes on five species of the amphipod genus Ampelisca from the stomach contents of the triglid fishes." volume="7" year="1959">Nagata (1959)</bibRefCitation>
. 
<bibRefCitation id="A2C38CD6989C9E58E279FC825900810A" author="Imbach, MC" journalOrPublisher="Naga Report" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="40 - 167" title="Scientific Result of Marine Investigation of the South China Sea and Gulf of Thailand: Gammaridean Amphipoda from the South China Sea." volume="4" year="1967">Imbach (1967)</bibRefCitation>
discussed some of the variations concerning this particular species and refuted the idea of naming the existing ecophenotypes reported by 
<bibRefCitation id="AD7739A8198F49F7C37FEDBEC5B222D0" author="Schellenberg, A" editor="Michaelsen, W" journalOrPublisher="L. Friedrichsohn &amp; Co., Hamburg" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" title="Crustacea. VIII: Amphipoda." year="1925">Schellenberg (1925)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EE8A8E4C20DDED6D77E67792DC7402E4" author="Reid, DM" journalOrPublisher="Atlantidae Report" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" pagination="190 - 291" title="Report on the Amphipoda (Gammaridea and Caprellidea) of the Coast of Tropical West Africa." volume="2" year="1951">Reid (1951)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="F50D108359E08530BFEF39DA9F3A88E6" author="Dahl, E" journalOrPublisher="Kungliga Fysiografiska Sallskapets i Lund Forhandlingar" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" title="Menigratopsis svennilssoni n. gen. et. spec., a lysianassid amphipod from The Sound." volume="15" year="1945">Dahl (1945)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="5DD0EB72A849D19EAEF16C30089DB92B" author="Pirlot, JM" journalOrPublisher="Siboga-Expeditie" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" pagination="237 - 328" title="Les amphipodes de l'expedition du Siboga. Deuxieme partie .... II. - Les amphipodes de la mer profonde. III. Les amphipodes littoraux. I. Lysianassidae ... Gammaridae." volume="33 e" year="1936">Pirlot (1936)</bibRefCitation>
as a subspecies due to their insignificant distinctions.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="009C0224C7181EB8025251B1762AE863" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="4" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
Taking into consideration that 
<taxonomicName id="2E2BE3DDCF84B6F66BB4751E8523E8D2" genus="Ampelicsa" lsidName="Ampelicsa brevicornis" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" rank="species" species="brevicornis">
<pageBreakToken id="93CEBF448CD7EE2C035B6A50E6BA3E26" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" start="start">Ampelicsa</pageBreakToken>
brevicornis
</taxonomicName>
is one of the most popular inhabitants on a littoral sea bottom and widely distributed on the sea floor of the east coast (South China Sea) and the west coast (Straits of Malacca) of Peninsular Malaysia, and numerous specimens have been meticulously examined, misidentification can be confidently ruled out. The specimens at hand show only minor disparities from 
<normalizedToken id="4B1B4E70F92ECC964D55DDF0F4188144" originalValue="Imbach’s">Imbach's</normalizedToken>
by having a broader propodus of pereopod 7, so it is clearly satisfactory to identify the specimens as 
<taxonomicName id="99C9B160C23FF18257BC11FCF0BA24D5" genus="Ampelicsa" lsidName="Ampelicsa brevicornis" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" rank="species" species="brevicornis">Ampelicsa brevicornis</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<caption id="51660D67C797C988CF519CCEEFA57A17" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<paragraph id="47B67A66221C3B4E518FCADC7F4CD172" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
